# Type surface review

Before writing any `pub` signature ‚Äî `pub fn`, `pub struct` with pub
fields, `pub trait` ‚Äî walk this checklist. It's short and
mechanical; skipping it is how drift re-enters the codebase.

## Step 1 ‚Äî decision test

For every type position (return type, parameter, field), ask:

> "Can I imagine two implementations with different behavior here?"

- Yes ‚Üí it's a trait slot. Use a trait bound (`&mut impl X`, `impl Y`,
  `<T: Z>`), not a concrete type.
- No ‚Üí look at the 4 type categories (Trait / Newtype / repr(C) enum
  / Primitive) in `.claude/rules/type-surface.md` and pick the right
  one.

## Step 2 ‚Äî primitive-vocabulary scan

Search the proposed signature for these forbidden shapes:

| Found | Replace with |
|-------|--------------|
| `Option<T>` | `notko::Maybe<T>` |
| `Result<T, E>` | `notko::Outcome<T, E>` (or `notko::Just<T>` on hot paths) |
| `Vec<T>` | `impl IntoIterator<Item = T>`, `&[T]`, or `&mut impl Collector<T>` |
| `HashMap<K, V>` | `&mut impl KeyValueStore<K, V>` or `Map<K, V, N: Cap>` |
| `String`, non-static `&str` | `&'static str` or `hilavitkutin_str::Str` |
| `usize` | `arvo::USize` (or `arvo::Cap` for const-generic capacity) |
| `u8..u128`, `i8..i128` | `arvo::UFixed<I, F, S>` / `arvo::IFixed<I, F, S>` / trait bound like `<T: UArith<BITS>>` |
| `f32`, `f64` | `arvo::FastFloat` / `arvo::StrictFloat` |
| `bool` | `arvo_bits::Bool` |

## Step 3 ‚Äî heap scan

Any allocation implied by the signature? The no_std universe has no
heap. Any `Vec`, `String`, `Box`, `Rc`, `Arc` in the proposed surface
means you've reached for the wrong tool. Reshape to a trait-bound
emitter or a bounded store.

## Step 4 ‚Äî red flags (stop and reshape)

If any of these match your proposed signature, STOP:

- Returning `Vec<Error>` or `Vec<T>` ‚Üí take a `&mut impl Sink<T>`
  parameter instead.
- Returning `String` ‚Üí write into a `&mut impl ByteEmitter` / take
  `&'static str`.
- `Box<dyn Trait>` ‚Üí monomorphise. `impl Trait` or `<T: Trait>`.
- `HashMap::new()` at runtime ‚Üí declare a `Map<K, V, N: Cap>` type
  and take a trait-bound reference.

## Step 5 ‚Äî if no existing trait fits

Don't reach for a std type. The correct answer is "add a trait to
the ecosystem" ‚Äî `hilavitkutin-api` for platform/context/access
traits, `arvo-bits` for bit-level contracts, a new sibling crate
for bespoke surfaces. File a design round describing the contract.

## Step 6 ‚Äî if none of the above and you still can't express it

The API shape is wrong. The no-heap + trait-first universe is strict
BY DESIGN. If the reshape feels heavier than "just use std", that's
friction the ecosystem should close (ship a shorthand, add to a
prelude), NOT a reason to escape to std. Reconsider the intent.

## Step 7 ‚Äî document the decision

In the signature's doc comment, note which trait bound / type you
picked and why. Future readers can audit quickly.

